<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-09-22T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-09-22T23:00:00-05:00" n="501" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d501">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/859: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Perkins</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-09-23T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">September 23,
                                        1928—noon</hi>.</date><lb/>[Received September 24—9:40
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>724. Department’s 323, September 20, 5 [<hi rend="italic">8</hi>] p.m. In
                            conversation with Admiral Bristol I have acquainted him with the
                            Department’s views regarding the use of naval forces in preventing
                            taxation <pb facs="0632" n="514" xml:id="pg_514"/> and regarding private
                            taxation arrangements as set forth in paragraph 7 of the Department’s
                            telegram above mentioned. I have also made available to him the text of
                            the Department’s two telegrams to the Legation referred to in that
                            paragraph.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>